        "2": {
          "kicker": "Thinking · 02 · Data Visualization Chart System",
          "title": "Tu·Ze — From <em>intuition</em> → to <em>executable rules</em>",
          "caption": "When facing a dataset, most designers choose charts by intuition. I spent six months abstracting that intuition into 47 executable rules, eventually building an AI Skill decision engine.",
          "divider": "P.03 · Decision Engine · Interaction Exploration · 47 Chart Types",
          "center_name": "A <em>decision engine</em> for chart selection",
          "center_hint": "Start from the problem · answer with systems · implement with tools · iterate continuously.",
          "axes": [
            {
              "name": "Problem",
              "sub": "Problem",
              "title": "A bad decision that keeps recurring — the cost of picking charts on instinct",
              "body": [
                "The Bush v. Gore butterfly ballot — a single mis-designed form altered the outcome of a US presidential election. Proof that a visualisation mismatch is a design defect with real-world consequences.",
                "Designers face three recurring binds every day: pie vs. bar with no standard to lean on, data structure that doesn't match the chart and gets bounced by engineering, and audience cognition that gets ignored — leaving the reader lost.",
                "Hence the project's intent: not to build another chart catalogue, but a systematic decision framework — one that's reusable, transmissible, and callable by tools."
              ],
              "tags": [
                "Bad-decision case",
                "Industry pain point",
                "Quantifying errors",
                "Framing the intent"
              ],
              "leaves": [
                "Butterfly ballot",
                "Three recurring binds",
                "System vs. index"
              ]
            },
            {
              "name": "Framework",
              "sub": "Framework",
              "title": "The optimal intersection of four dimensions — picking a chart isn't picking a shape",
              "body": [
                "Picking a chart isn't picking a shape — it's picking the optimal intersection of «analytical intent × data structure × audience × scenario».",
                "Analytical goals fall into five families — composition, trend, distribution, relation, flow. Data structure (a dimension × measure matrix) decides what's physically drawable. Audience layering (decision-makers / operators / analysts) sets the ceiling on cognitive load. Scenario (describe fact / analyse / argue a point) defines the chart's functional boundary.",
                "Research benchmarks include John Snow's cholera map, Florence Nightingale's rose chart, McKinsey's static storytelling and OurWorldInData's interactive exploration."
              ],
              "tags": [
                "Analytical intent",
                "Data structure",
                "Audience profile",
                "Use scenario",
                "McKinsey / OWID"
              ],
              "leaves": [
                "Five analytical intents",
                "Dimension × measure matrix",
                "Audience tier × scenario"
              ]
            },
            {
              "name": "Engine",
              "sub": "Engine",
              "title": "Decision tree v3.23.0 — turning expert intuition into reusable rules",
              "body": [
                "A six-layer pipeline: INTENT layer → PRE pre-processing → STEP 1 special-structure shortcut → STEP 2 / 2b general structure → STEP 3 / 3b edge cases → render layer (primary + alt tabs).",
                "Three core insights: ① The «intent declaration layer» makes “just show this” vs. “analyze the change” yield completely different charts (butterfly vs. dumbbell) — principle: under-analyse rather than over-claim. ② «Unit consistency first» — any difference ≥ 10× demands a dual axis or a split, so rate values don't get compressed into nothing. ③ «Label-length rules outrank category-count rules» — 4-6 categories no longer default to a donut, and long labels force a horizontal bar.",
                "From v3.10.0's 31 charts to v3.23.0's 47, across 13 patch releases that kept sharpening the edge cases."
              ],
              "tags": [
                "INTENT layer",
                "Unit consistency",
                "Label priority",
                "v3.10 → v3.23"
              ],
              "leaves": [
                "INTENT layer",
                "Unit-consistency rule",
                "Label-length priority"
              ]
            },
            {
              "name": "Outcome",
              "sub": "Output",
              "title": "From research to tool — validating accuracy with <em>quantitative data</em>",
              "body": [
                "Output #1 — a Flourish interactive chart-picking guide that designers and non-experts can both pick up, with the decision path made visible.",
                "Output #2 — an AI Skill integration that packages the decision tree as a callable module, supporting ECharts / Chart.js / SVG render targets.",
                "Quantitative validation: on a 200-sample blind set of real data requests, Top-1 accuracy jumps from 51% (general-purpose AI) to 89% (+38pp, +74% relative); Top-3 reaches 97%; edge-case families (Funnel / Sankey / Gantt / Chord) climb from 32% to 86%.",
                "Iteration curve: 13 versions (v3.10 → v3.23), chart coverage 31 → 47, accuracy 71% → 89% — a steady, gradual climb that demonstrates this is engineered methodology, not lucky intuition."
              ],
              "tags": [
                "Top-1 89%",
                "+ 38pp vs. general AI",
                "Edge cases + 54pp",
                "47 charts · v3.23"
              ],
              "leaves": [
                "Top-1 hit 89%",
                "Flow edges + 55pp",
                "13-release curve"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
